‘A Feast of Art’ art show will be held in the beautiful Historic Oxley Hall.
 
The Gala Opening Night will be at 7:00pm on Friday 7 September and winning artists will be presented with their prizes on the night. All welcome, refreshments available.
 
Prizes will be awarded to the winning artist in each section: Visual Art; Photographic Art; and Textiles.
also, Highly Commended in each section.
 
This local art show provides artists with an opportunity to display and sell their works over a period of 10 days, gaining maximum exposure of their work.
 
All art works will be for sale following prize giving on Opening Night. With paintings, drawings, photography and textile art on display there will be something for everyone to enjoy.
 
Open 10:00am to 4:00pm daily (closing 3:00pm on last day).

products.productName: 'Blue Feet' by Marsha Wajer @ Balnaves of Coonawarra
products.productDescription:
“Blue Feet” an exhibition by illustrator Marsha Wajer, showcases those gorgeous, goofy dancers…the Blue Footed Boobys. 
Why do they love to dance? Why do they show their feet off all the time? 
Marsha has created a delightful series around these (increasingly) rare and cute birds. It’s full of fun, it’s full of colour and has iguanas, octopuses and stripey hats included!

“Moo and the Sleepy Secret” (illustrated by Marsha) will also be read aloud 
by the author (Catherine Clarke) out in the garden. Followed by a drawing demonstration where the kids can join in. Crayons and paper provided.
Cupcakes for the kids and wine for the adults will be available to purchase.

products.owningOrganisationName: The Trustee for the Veterans Benevolent Fund
products.productDescription:
The RSL and Services Association, through the Veterans Benevolent Fund, is holding its annual “Honour Our Heroes” Relay Walk . The relay is 42 kilometres long (one kilometre for every Australian killed while serving in Afghanistan). 

The Veterans Benevolent Fund, working in partnership with RSL and Services Clubs Association and other agencies, is set to give the public an opportunity to raise much needed funds for the Homes for Heroes initiative. 

Many Defence personnel return from active service suffering from Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD) as a result of the horrific situations they confront in the line of duty.

Artisan on Lewis presents a selection of Felicity’s fun wire sculptures mounted on timber stands alongside her vivid acrylic painted vistas. 

Multi-skilled Mudgee artist Felicity Cavanough aims to inspire joy through her artworks capturing fun fleeting moments in her life shared with a young family.  “I like art that moves. My sculptures reflect everyday activity and are designed to wobble accordingly”. 

A visit to her local scrap and steel yard stimulates her visionary process resulting in a car full of ‘treasure’ of both timber and wire varieties. Felicity’s sculptures are presented as still sketches but when you realise the thought put into every twist and curve of wire you will be amazed at her skillful technique. 

Graduating with a Bachelor of Fine Arts (UNSW) 23 years ago, Felicity teaches and practices art and is involved in the local visual art scene in picturesque Mudgee. She regularly exhibits in the annual Sculptures in the Garden at Rosby, Mudgee and the Mid West Waste to Art competition to great success, she has recently won the Artist's Choice Award in the Gauge Gallery Glebe 'Just Art' competition 2017 and the People's Choice Award at the 2017 York festival in Western Australia.

products.productName: 'So That You Might Know Each Other': Faith and Culture in Islam
products.productDescription: View intriguing objects —  from clothing and ceremonial hangings to musical instruments, armour, precious manuscripts, ceramics and jewellery — that celebrate the achievements of Muslim people across the world, their daily lives, traditions and spirituality.

"George" The Giant Squid can be found on display in The Wallaroo Heritage and Nautical Museum.  George was found in the stomach of a whale off the coast of Albany - Western Australia in the late 1970's. He was donated to the Wallaroo Heritage and Nautical Museum in 1984. He has recently been placed in a new tank, along with a new solution of glycerin, you can see him in this tank without any discoloration as he should be. Local school children from St Mary MacKillop School drew pictures of 'George' which are also on display around 'George'. Please come and visit 'George' in his new home.

Entry fee includes admission to  all exhibits at Wallaroo Heritage and Nautical Museum, $6 adults and Children between 5 and 16 - $3, open 7 days a week 10am to 4pm.

Yarri and Jacky Jacky stand on the corner of Kitchener and Sheridan Streets.  A larger than life-size, bronze sculpture to commemorate the 165th anniversary of the Great Flood of Gundagai in 1852.
The sculpture celebrates the heroic work of Yarri and Jacky Jacky, along with other members of the Wiradjuri tribe in saving some 69 townsfolk from the flood waters.

On the night of June 24, 1852 two Wiradjuri men, Yarri and Jacky Jacky, rescued one third of the Gundagai town's residents in frail bark canoes from the flooded Murrumbidgee River.  It was a protracted rescue effort, continuing over some days and nights.

This sculpture is a must see in this beautiful country town!

Extracting contemporary gestural motif from Aboriginal archetypes, [Mis]conceive’s hip-hop, physical percussion and rhythmic cultural pattern is expressive and immediate.

Through the assertion of a continuous Aboriginal dance canon, the aesthetic rejects, reveals and re-educates modern (mis)-understandings of Indigeneity, [Mis]conceive argues that knowledge does not equal comprehension. Books are not their covers. One size does not fit all.

Kelly and his ensemble move with assured physicality in this high-energy work that pulses with humour, play and personal stories. Voice and body become pathways to traditional dance and song, as repetition and disguise make way for moments of discovery.

[Mis]conceive brings audiences through the past, to understand the present, and move forward into a better future.

Mansfield Musical and Dramatic Society (MMuDS) presents the musical comedy [title of show]

Jeff and Hunter, two struggling writers, hear about a new musical theatre festival. However, the deadline for submissions is a mere three weeks away. With nothing to lose, the pair decides to try to create something new with the help of their friends Susan, Heidi and Larry on the eighty-eights. With the cast in place, Jeff and Hunter begin a conversation about what to write about. Eventually, Jeff suggests they write about what to write about. They make a pact to write up until the festival's deadline and dream about the show changing their lives.

In the span of 90 minutes they write and perform their show at the festival and learn lessons about themselves as people, friends and artists. [title of show] is, above all, a love letter to the musical theatre, a uniquely American art form, and to the joy of collaboration.

This show contains low level occasional bad language. The show is probably not suitable for very young children.

With 33 race meetings yearly, the Alice Springs Turf Club have always got something exciting happening for families, party fanatics and racing enthusiasts! 

The Turf Club's signature series of events is the Ladbrokes Alice Springs Cup Carnival in April-May 2018. Race days include The Mercure Alice Springs Resort Ladies Day, Coca Cola Family Day, Young Guns Day, Holdfast Insurance Brokers Pioneer Sprint Day and the Ladbrokes Alice Springs Cup Day on the May Day public holiday. The $110,000 Ladbrokes Alice Springs Cup is the largest race for prize money in the annual racing calendar for remote Central Australia. 

The Alice Springs Turf Club hosts the Spring Carnival of racing, which includes October-November racing, Melbourne Cup Day and Young Guns Two.
